{"type":"hook.start","data":{"hookInvocationId":"91f15f46-545b-4cc2-9145-36b5124c3e0e","hookType":"postToolUse","input":{"sessionId":"07c40cd0-ff51-4d6e-bdcd-ac2f90877203","timestamp":1774039631468,"cwd":"D:\\Source\\GitHub\\agent-engram","toolName":"view","toolArgs":{"path":"D:\\Source\\GitHub\\agent-engram\\.context\\backlog.md","view_range":[5,506]},"toolResult":{"resultType":"success","textResultForLlm":"5. ## Feature 007\r\n6. \r\n7. **Strategic pivot decided 2026-03-19**: Strip all task management. Specialize on code intelligence only. See \"Strip Task Management\" spec below.\r\n8. \r\n9. ## Strip Task Management: Specialize Engram as a Code Intelligence Server\r\n10. \r\n11. **Priority**: Critical — architectural pivot that redefines the project's scope and purpose\r\n12. **Discovered**: 2026-03-19 during strategic review of project direction\r\n13. **Supersedes**: All task management feature requests; partially supersedes \"Phased Startup\" (task-related phasing becomes irrelevant)\r\n14. **Related**: \"Optimize SurrealDB Usage\" (retained and elevated — code graph queries become the entire product)\r\n15. \r\n16. ### Motivation\r\n17. \r\n18. Agent-engram was originally conceived as a dual-purpose MCP daemon: persistent task memory *and* code intelligence for AI coding assistants. External tools like Beads (`bd`) now handle task tracking with superior Git-native workflows, dependency-aware scheduling, and multi-agent coordination. Maintaining a parallel task management system inside engram creates redundancy, inflates the binary, bloats the MCP tool surface (24 of 45 tools are task-related), and — most critically — wastes context window tokens when agents discover and reason about tools they will never use because Beads already covers that domain.\r\n19. \r\n20. The strategic pivot: strip all task management functionality and focus engram exclusively on **code mapping, code graph synchronization, semantic search, and workspace content intelligence**. This aligns with the original insight in the first backlog entry: the spec/task process was never the right fit for an MCP daemon. The value of engram is in providing agents with a persistent, queryable model of the codebase structure — call graphs, import trees, symbol relationships, semantic similarity — that survives across context window resets and agent sessions.\r\n21. \r\n22. ### Goals\r\n23. \r\n24. 1. Eliminate all task management MCP tools, models, database tables, services, and persistence files\r\n25. 2. Reduce the MCP tool surface from 45 tools to approximately 15-18 focused code intelligence tools\r\n26. 3. Shrink binary size and startup time by removing task-related dependencies, hydration/dehydration of task files, and event ledger overhead\r\n27. 4. Simplify the `.engram/` directory to contain only code graph state, workspace config, and content records\r\n28. 5. Reduce context window consumption by presenting agents with a smaller, coherent tool surface focused on a single domain\r\n29. 6. Preserve and elevate all code graph, search, embedding, and workspace content intelligence capabilities\r\n30. \r\n31. ### Scope of Removal\r\n32. \r\n33. This section inventories every component that must be removed, organized by layer.\r\n34. \r\n35. #### MCP Tools to Remove (24 tools)\r\n36. \r\n37. | Tool | Module | Category |\r\n38. |------|--------|----------|\r\n39. | `create_task` | write.rs | Task CRUD |\r\n40. | `update_task` | write.rs | Task CRUD |\r\n41. | `claim_task` | write.rs | Task CRUD |\r\n42. | `release_task` | write.rs | Task CRUD |\r\n43. | `batch_update_tasks` | write.rs | Task CRUD |\r\n44. | `defer_task` | write.rs | Task deferral |\r\n45. | `undefer_task` | write.rs | Task deferral |\r\n46. | `pin_task` | write.rs | Task pinning |\r\n47. | `unpin_task` | write.rs | Task pinning |\r\n48. | `add_blocker` | write.rs | Dependencies |\r\n49. | `add_dependency` | write.rs | Dependencies |\r\n50. | `get_task_graph` | read.rs | Dependencies |\r\n51.